text:
Instead of data-driven instruction, how about instruction-driven data?

I forget where I heard this but I think it's pithy. Focus on collecting the data you know how to use to inform instruction, rather than on sifting through data that may or may not be helpful.

#MTBoS

@KauDan721 @kauf_quinn Some ideas:
* Add 1 to both numbers and then subtract.
* Find the differences to landmark numbers like 40 and 50, and then add these differences and 10 to find the total distance.
*Change the first number to 50 + 7 and the second to 30 + 9. 50-30 = 20. 7-9 =-2, then 20-2 = 18.

text:
@davidwees I pondered this all day.

Parallelograms are a subset of quadrilaterals. Kites are another subset of quadrilaterals. Rectangles are a subset of parallelograms. Rhombuses are the intersection of parallelograms and kites. Squares are the intersection of rhombuses and rectangles. https://t.co/T1WOOrkwgw

text:
For forty values of n, n¬≤ + n + 41 is prime (source: https://t.co/Hcb1zCcMIf) but after that, it's no longer prime. The pattern breaks.

If you patterning regularly with your students, they'll need some counter-examples at least once in a while.
bbox_coords: NA NA NA NA NA NA NA NA
name: David Wees
description: Father. Canadian, Math Curriculum Designer for @DreamBox_Learn. Love science. Geek, Feminist, Humanist, Anti-Racist, Passionate about education. #MTBoS He/Him

text:
The one caveat to looking for patterns though is that sometimes they break.

eg. Look at the values of n¬≤ + n + 41.
n = 1, (1)¬≤ + (1) + 41 = 43
n = 2, (2)¬≤ + (2) + 41 = 47
n = 3, (3)¬≤ + (3) + 41 = 53
n = 4, (4)¬≤ + (4) + 41 = 71

Each of these answers is prime! Whoa!
bbox_coords: NA NA NA NA NA NA NA NA

text: It is often the case though that mathematicians look for patterns first and then look for explanations for those patterns next.

text: The "without comment" bit while sharing the paired examples is crucial, by the way. Linking examples is already challenging work, your words will only distract students. You can give them 10-20 seconds to quietly think on their own.

text: At the last step, you pause and have students describe the connections they see while using talk moves like asking a student to revoice or rephrase what another student shares while capturing the connections with annotation. Ideally, this is all captured somewhere semi-permanent.

text: Imagine each of these slides being shared one at a time, so as not to overwhelm students, and without comment. Students look at the examples, look for connections, share connections briefly with a partner, and then you can select one or two students to share with the class.

text:
Here's another routine structure I've been thinking about. Paired examples. The basic idea is that you give students a pair of examples worked out, one step at a time. One that students know paired with one that they do not.
